":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: ethnic name for a Breton, from Old French <i>bret</i>, nominative of <i>breton</i> ‘Breton’ (see   Breton  ). See also English   Brett  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Breton","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Andre, Normand, Renald, Adelard, Alphonse, Armand, Gaetan, Laurent, Serge, Adrien, Aime.","French, Breton (mainly Finistère), and English (of Norman origin): ethnic name for a Breton, from Old French <i>breton</i>, oblique case of <i>bret</i> (see   Bret  ). Compare   Lebreton  , see also English   Brett  .","History: In North America, this surname was originally also a secondary surname or <i>dit</i> (‘also called’) name, borne by Jean Élie/Hélie <i>dit</i> (Le) Breton from Ménéac in Morbihan, Brittany (France), who married Jeanne Labbé in Sainte-Famille, Île d'Orléans, QC, in 1669. His descendants also bear the surname   Elie  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"Le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Lewis   or respelling of   Lou  , as borne by the impresario  Lew Grade  (  1906–98 , originally  Louis Winogradsky )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":17,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":30,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Le Bret was born in 1298, in Weston, Somerset, England, her father, Sir Richard le Bret, was 29 and her mother, Joan Achard, was 3. She married John de Raleigh in 1320. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died after 1335, in Somerset, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1298–after 1335":"1298–pärast 1335","1298–1335":"1298–1335","1265–1340":"1265–1340","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","1335–1372":"1335–1372","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1270–1323":"1270–1323","1295–1348":"1295–1348","before 1323":"enne 1323","1340":"1340","1372":"1372","1295":"1295","1270":"1270","after 1335":"pärast 1335","1315":"1315","1348":"1348","1335":"1335","1323":"1323","1298":"1298","1320":"1320","1265":"1265","about 1320":"umbes 1320","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Weston, Somerset, England":"Weston, Somerset, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"1298–after 1335":"1298–1335 jälkeen","1298–1335":"1298–1335","1265–1340":"1265–1340","1295–Male":"1295–Kuollut","1335–1372":"1335–1372","1320–Female":"1320–Kuollut","1270–1323":"1270–1323","1295–1348":"1295–1348","before 1323":"ennen vuotta 1323","1340":"1340","1372":"1372","1295":"1295","1270":"1270","after 1335":"1335 jälkeen","1315":"1315","1348":"1348","1335":"1335","1323":"1323","1298":"1298","1320":"1320","1265":"1265","about 1320":"noin 1320","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Somerset, England":"Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Weston, Somerset, England":"Weston, Somerset, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fr":{"1298–after 1335":"1298–après 1335","1298–1335":"1298–1335","1265–1340":"